          },
          "pause": true,
          "displayType": "poster",
          "buttonOnMobile": false,
          "label": "<p>The patient described has leg pain radiating from the buttock to the foot, canno</p>",
          "x": 30,
          "y": 30,
          "width": 40,
          "height": 25,
          "libraryTitle": "Multiple Choice",
          "action": {
            "library": "H5P.MultiChoice 1.16",
            "params": {
              "question": "<p>The patient described has leg pain radiating from the buttock to the foot, cannot raise his leg beyond 30 degrees, and has an absent ankle jerk. These findings together suggest nerve root compression at which level of the spine?</p>",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "<div>Cervical spine</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Cervical root compression causes upper limb symptoms such as arm pain and hand numbness, not lower limb radiculopathy with an absent ankle jerk.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Thoracic spine</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Thoracic disc herniations are rare and present with band-like chest or abdominal pain, not the lower limb radicular pain and reflex loss described here.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Lumbar spine</div>",
                  "correct": true,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Correct. Unilateral lower-limb radicular pain, a restricted straight leg raise, and an absent ankle jerk together localise the lesion to a lumbar nerve root — most commonly compressed by a prolapsed intervertebral disc.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Sacral spine below S2</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Lesions below S2 affect the cauda equina diffusely, causing bilateral symptoms and bladder dysfunction rather than the unilateral leg pain with a single lost reflex described here.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                }
              ],
              "overallFeedback": [
                {
                  "from": 0,
                  "to": 50,
                  "feedback": "The combination of dermatomal leg pain, a positive straight leg raise, and an absent ankle jerk is the classic presentation of lumbar nerve root compression by a prolapsed intervertebral disc."
                },
                {
                  "from": 51,
                  "to": 100,
                  "feedback": "Well done. Disc prolapse at the lumbar level is the most common spinal condition presenting to Indian hospitals, and anatomical localisation guides the decision to operate."
                }
              ],
              "behaviour": {
