          },
          "pause": true,
          "displayType": "poster",
          "buttonOnMobile": false,
          "label": "<p>The posterior longitudinal ligament narrows as it descends the vertebral canal. </p>",
          "x": 30,
          "y": 30,
          "width": 40,
          "height": 25,
          "libraryTitle": "Multiple Choice",
          "action": {
            "library": "H5P.MultiChoice 1.16",
            "params": {
              "question": "<p>The posterior longitudinal ligament narrows as it descends the vertebral canal. Which clinical consequence does this anatomical feature most directly predispose to?</p>",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "<div>Hyperextension injury of the cervical spine</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Hyperextension is resisted by the anterior longitudinal ligament, which runs along the front of the vertebral bodies. The posterior longitudinal ligament lies inside the canal and protects the posterior disc surface.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Posterolateral herniation of the intervertebral disc</div>",
                  "correct": true,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Correct. As the posterior longitudinal ligament narrows at its edges, the posterolateral portion of the annulus fibrosus — already the thinnest part of the disc — is left unprotected, making it the commonest site for disc herniation.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Anterior compression fracture of the vertebral body</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Compression fractures result from axial loading on osteoporotic or diseased bone. They are unrelated to the narrowing pattern of the posterior longitudinal ligament.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Hypertrophy of the ligamentum flavum</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Ligamentum flavum hypertrophy is a degenerative change in the elastic ligament connecting adjacent laminae. It causes spinal stenosis but is unrelated to the posterior longitudinal ligament's narrowing.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                }
              ],
              "overallFeedback": [
                {
                  "from": 0,
                  "to": 50,
                  "feedback": "The posterior longitudinal ligament protects the midline posterior disc but narrows at its lateral edges as it descends, leaving the posterolateral annulus — the thinnest part of the disc — as the weakest and most herniation-prone zone."
                },
                {
                  "from": 51,
                  "to": 100,
                  "feedback": "Exactly right. The narrowing of the PLL explains why roughly 95 per cent of disc herniations occur posterolaterally, most commonly at L4–L5 and L5–S1."
                }
              ],
              "behaviour": {
                "enableRetry": true,
                "enableSolutionsButton": true,
