          },
          "pause": true,
          "displayType": "poster",
          "buttonOnMobile": false,
          "label": "<p>In scoliosis, the characteristic rib hump detected on Adam's forward bending tes</p>",
          "x": 30,
          "y": 30,
          "width": 40,
          "height": 25,
          "libraryTitle": "Multiple Choice",
          "action": {
            "library": "H5P.MultiChoice 1.16",
            "params": {
              "question": "<p>In scoliosis, the characteristic rib hump detected on Adam's forward bending test is produced by:</p>",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "<div>Collapse of vertebral bodies on the concave side of the curve</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Vertebral body collapse is a feature of osteoporotic compression fractures or Pott's disease. The rib hump in scoliosis is a rotational deformity, not a compressive one.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Rotation of vertebrae pushing the ribs posteriorly on the convex side</div>",
                  "correct": true,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Correct. Scoliosis involves lateral curvature plus vertebral rotation. This rotation displaces the attached ribs posteriorly on the convex side, producing the rib hump that becomes most prominent when the patient bends forward.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Spasm of the erector spinae muscles on the concave side</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>While paravertebral muscle asymmetry may be present, the rib hump is a structural bony deformity caused by vertebral rotation displacing the ribs, not by muscle spasm alone.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Forward slippage of thoracic vertebrae over one another</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Forward vertebral slippage is spondylolisthesis, a separate condition caused by a stress fracture of the pars interarticularis, typically at the lumbar level. It does not produce a rib hump.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                }
              ],
              "overallFeedback": [
                {
                  "from": 0,
                  "to": 50,
                  "feedback": "In scoliosis, vertebrae rotate as they curve laterally. This rotation pushes the attached ribs posteriorly on the convex side, creating the rib hump. Adam's forward bending test accentuates this deformity and is the standard screening tool."
                },
                {
                  "from": 51,
                  "to": 100,
                  "feedback": "Well done. The three-dimensional nature of scoliosis — lateral curvature plus rotation — is the key. A Cobb angle above 10 degrees confirms the diagnosis, and Adam's forward bending test is the standard screening method."
                }
              ],
              "behaviour": {
